Reasoning: Mathematical models predict that Artemisinin-based combination therapy (ACTs) have a dramatic impact in reducing malaria transmission. Paper ID 1805641, "Modelling the Impact of Artemisinin Combination Therapy and Long-Acting Treatments on Malaria Transmission Intensity," directly supports this claim. The paper states that artemisinin derivatives in ACTs significantly lower patient infectiousness and have the potential to reduce population-level transmission of Plasmodium falciparum (prop_1423, prop_1424). A mathematical model was developed to predict the impact of introducing ACT as first-line treatment for uncomplicated malaria (prop_1426), and the study estimated the reduction in transmission achieved by different types of treatment (prop_1425). The results suggest that ACTs have the potential for transmission reductions approaching those achieved by insecticide-treated nets in lower-transmission settings (prop_1436). Specifically, a 53% reduction in prevalence of infection was predicted if 100% of current treatment was switched to ACT in areas with low baseline slide-prevalence (prop_1429). The abstract further confirms that the study used a mathematical model to estimate the reduction in transmission achieved by introducing different types of treatment for symptomatic P. falciparum malaria.
